Udacity Machine Learning Nanodegree Capstone Project¶

The challenge for this project is to build a model, which can calculate and predict the price of real estate based on data collected in Melbourne. This problem will be solved in two different ways:

  1. Building regression models using scikit learn library
  2. Building neural net using keras library

Solution #1: Regression models¶

1. Load data¶

# Calculating and plotiing feature importance based on RandomForestRegressor
def model_run(dataframe):
    X_try_clean = dataframe.drop('Price', axis=1)
    y_try_clean = dataframe.Price
    X_try_train_clean, X_try_test_clean, y_try_train_clean, y_try_test_clean = train_test_split(X_try_clean, y_try_clean, test_size=0.2, random_state= 42)
    feat_reg = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100)
    time_start = time()
    feat_reg.fit(X_try_train_clean,y_try_train_clean)
    y_pred = feat_reg.predict(X_try_test_clean)
    print('Fit-predict time: {:.3f} sec'.format(time()-time_start))
    print('RMSE: {:.3f}'.format(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_try_test_clean, y_pred))))
    print('Score: {:.3f}'.format(feat_reg.score(X_try_test_clean, y_try_test_clean)))
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.bar(dataframe.drop('Price', axis=1).columns,feat_reg.feature_importances_)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel('Feature importance')
    plt.savefig('fig5.jpeg')
    plt.show()

# Converts all missing values in the specified column to the median
def missing_median(df, name):
    med = df[name].median()
    df[name] = df[name].fillna(med)

#Loss plot
def plotting_loss(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], lw=2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], lw=2)
    plt.title('model loss')
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='best')
    #plt.ylim(0, 4*1e11)
    plt.show()
    
# Regression plot
def chart_regression(pred,y,sort=True):
    df = pd.DataFrame({'pred' : pred, 'y' : y})
    if sort:
        df.sort_values(by=['y'],inplace=True)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    a = plt.plot(df['y'].tolist(),lw=5, label='expected')
    b = plt.plot(df['pred'].tolist(),lw=1, alpha=0.7,label='prediction')
    plt.ylabel('Price')
    plt.xlabel('number of testing datapoints')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# RMSE plot
def plot_history(hist):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Root Mean Square Error')
    plt.plot(hist['epoch'], np.sqrt(hist['mean_squared_error']),
           label='Train Error')
    plt.plot(hist['epoch'], np.sqrt(hist['val_mean_squared_error']),
           label = 'Val Error')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

3. Exploring regression models¶

3.1 Trainig methods and evaluation metrics¶

Mean Square Error¶

The mean square error is the sum of the squared differences between the prediction ($\hat{y}$) and the expected ($y$). MSE values are not of a particular unit. Low MSE values are desired.

$\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left(\hat{y}_i - y_i\right)^2$

Root Mean Square Error¶

The root mean square (RMSE) is essentially the square root of the MSE. Because of this, the RMSE error is in the same units as the training data outcome. Low RMSE values are desired.

$\text{RMSE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left(\hat{y}_i - y_i\right)^2}$

Training with Cross-Validation and holdout set¶

Cross-Validation uses a number of folds, and multiple models, to generate out of sample predictions on the entire dataset. In this case there will be one model (neural network) for each fold. Each model contributes part of the final out-of-sample prediction.

3.2 Investigating different regression models¶

In this section the best predictive model will be chosen between following models from scikit learn library:

  • DecisionTreeRegressor
  • GradientBoostingRegressor
  • RandomForestRegressor
  • KNeighborsRegressor
  • PLSRegression
  • BayesianRidge
  • HuberRegressor
  • ExtraTreesRegressor
  • AdaBoostRegressor
  • XGBRegressor
In [36]:
# Suppressing future warnings
import warnings
warnings.simplefilter(action='ignore', category=FutureWarning)

# model inititlizing
clf_A = DecisionTreeRegressor()
clf_B = GradientBoostingRegressor()
clf_C = RandomForestRegressor()
clf_D = KNeighborsRegressor()
clf_E = PLSRegression()
clf_F = BayesianRidge()
clf_G = HuberRegressor(max_iter=1e4)
clf_H = ExtraTreesRegressor()
clf_I = AdaBoostRegressor()
clf_J = XGBRegressor()


# list initilizing
results=[]
alg=[]
time_l=[]
rmse_l=[]

# Looping over each model and calculating the cross validation score, calculation time and RMSE
for clf in [clf_A, clf_B,clf_C,clf_D,clf_E,clf_F,clf_G,clf_H,clf_I,clf_J]:
    # list of cross validation scores
    cv_results = cross_val_score(clf, X_main, y_main, cv = 5, scoring = 'r2')
    results.append(cv_results)
    start=time()
    clf = clf.fit(X_main, y_main)
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_holdout)
    end=time()
    alg.append(clf.__class__.__name__)
    # list of calculation times
    time_l.append(end-start)
    #computing RMSE
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_holdout, y_pred))
    rmse_l.append(rmse)
    msg = "{:25} --> cross_val_score: {:.3f}, RMSE: {:.3f} in {:.3f} sec".format(clf.__class__.__name__, cv_results.mean(), rmse, end-start)   
    print(msg)
    print(80*'=')

3.3 Tuning the hyperparameters¶

In [38]:
#Defining a function to find better hyperparameters for the model
def model_opt(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,reg,par,scorer='r2',cv=5):
    """ Performs grid search over the different parameter for a 
        given regressor trained on the input data [X_train, y_train]. """
    grid = RandomizedSearchCV(reg, par, scoring=scorer, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, n_iter=20)
    grid = grid.fit(X_train,y_train)
    model = grid.best_estimator_
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    r_score = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    score_to_bm = 100*(bench_mod_score-r_score)/bench_mod_score
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    rmse_to_bm = 100*(bench_mod_rmse-rmse)/bench_mod_rmse
    print('Best parameters of {} are: {}'.format(reg.__class__.__name__, grid.best_params_))
    print('r2_score of optimized {}: {:.3f}'.format(reg.__class__.__name__, r_score))
    print('Delta r_score to benchmar kmodel: {:.1f}%'.format(score_to_bm))
    print('RMSE of optimized {}: {:.3f}'.format(reg.__class__.__name__, rmse))
    print('Delta RMSE to benchmar kmodel: {:.1f}%'.format(rmse_to_bm))

    return y_pred, rmse, r_score

Solution 2: Neural net¶

4. Building the neural network¶

The second approach to predict the prices of real esate will be building of neural network. For this approach we will be using a cross validation technique with hold out set for final evaluating of the model on unseen data

4.1 Building and trainig the neural net on trainig set using K-Fold cross validation¶

In [50]:
# Using K-Fold cross validation with 10 folds
kf=KFold(10)
fold = 0

#out of sample lists
oos_y = []
oos_pred = []

#initializing min RSME
min_rmse=1e6

# trainig and validating the model using X_main (training data set)
for train, test in kf.split(X_main):
    fold+=1
    print("Fold #{}".format(fold))

    X_train_kf = X_main[train]
    y_train_kf = y_main[train]
    X_test_kf = X_main[test]
    y_test_kf = y_main[test]

    #Building a neural net
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(240, input_dim=X_main.shape[1], activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(Dense(120, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(Dense(60, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear')) 

    model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='Adam',metrics=['mse','mae'])
    model.optimizer.lr=0.001

    # model training
    history=model.fit(X_train_kf,y_train_kf,validation_data=(X_test_kf,y_test_kf), batch_size=500, verbose=0,epochs=500)

    # prediction on validating set
    pred = model.predict(X_test_kf)  

    # building two lists: with real and predicted values
    oos_y.append(y_test_kf)
    oos_pred.append(pred)

    # Measure this fold's RMSE
    score = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_kf,pred))
    print("Fold score (RMSE): {:.3f}".format(score))

    #Looking for the best NN and saving it to a file
    if score < min_rmse:
        # saving model to YAML
        model_yaml = model.to_yaml()
        with open("model.yaml", "w") as yaml_file:
            yaml_file.write(model_yaml)

        # saving weights to HDF5
        model.save_weights("model.h5")

        #updating min RMSE
        min_rmse = min(min_rmse,score)    
        print("Min score (RMSE): {:.3f}".format(min_rmse))

        # ploting charts for new best model
        hist = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
        hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
        plot_history(hist)
        plotting_loss(history)
        chart_regression(pred.ravel(),y_test_kf.ravel())
